Google Data Analytics Case Study: How Does a Bike-Share Navigate Speedy Success?

Vlad Bularca

11/10/2021

Overview

Scenario

You are a junior data analyst working in the marketing analyst team at Cyclistic, a bike-share company in Chicago. The director of marketing believes the companys future success depends on maximizing the number of annual memberships. Therefore, your team wants to understand how casual riders and annual members use Cyclistic bikes differently. From these insights, your team will design a new marketing strategy to convert casual riders into annual members. But first, Cyclistic executives must approve your recommendations, so they must be backed up with compelling data insights and professional data visualizations.

About the Company

Until now, Cyclistics marketing strategy relied on building general awareness and appealing to broad consumer segments. One approach that helped make these things possible was the flexibility of its pricing plans: single-ride passes, full-day passes, and annual memberships. Customers who purchase single-ride or full-day passes are referred to as casual riders. Customers who purchase annual memberships are Cyclistic members.

Cyclistics finance analysts have concluded that annual members are much more profitable than casual riders. Lily Moreno, the Director of Marketing, believes that there is a very good chance to convert casual riders into members, as opposed to creating a marketing campaign that targets all-new customers. She notes that casual riders are already aware of the Cyclistic program and have chosen Cyclistic for their mobility needs.

Moreno has set a clear goal: Design marketing strategies aimed at converting casual riders into annual members. In order to do that, however, the marketing analyst team needs to better understand how annual members and casual riders differ, why casual riders would buy a membership, and how digital media could affect their marketing tactics. Moreno and her team are interested in analyzing the Cyclistic historical bike trip data to identify trends.

My Responsibilities

In this scenario, I am a Junior Data Analyst that will use the data provided by the company to find out how casual riders and members use the service differently and how these insights can be used to help the marketing analyst team develop a data driven marketing strategy.

I will be documenting my entire work process in this document. I will cover how I cleaned and processed the data and how I used it to generate insights and develop recommendations so that Cyclistic can achieve its goals moving forward.

Data Source

The Data used for this project was Cyclisitcs historical trip data. The previous 12 months of trip data are available publicly: https://divvy-tripdata.s3.amazonaws.com/index.html

The data set I used is composed of 12 monthly data files that make up a year of bike share trips. I started by analyzing each of the monthly files using Excel. I checked the integrity of the data and did a quick cleaning process before further analyzing it using R studio.

Important Questions

Before I went any further with my analysis, I considered what the data could help me discover and some of the questions I need to answer:

  • What are the top 10 busiest stations?
  • What are busiest stations for members vs.casual riders?
  • How many total trips are there?
  • What is the average ride length for members and casual riders?
  • How do casual riders and members differ based on day of the week, and hour of the day?

Data Processing and Cleaning

When I first opened the CSV files in Excel, I noticed the large number of rows, ranging from 80,00 to 700,000 rows for each month of trips. The large size of the files made Excel slow, but I was able to make sense of the data and clean it. My steps to clean the data included:

  • Deleting rows that had important information missing. I actually had to upload the CSV files to BigQuery because some of the files were to large for Excel to process. I was able to remove rows with blanks using DELETE FROM
  • Making sure the format was consistent for each of the columns
  • Creating a new column called ride_length which calculated the time difference between the start of each trip and the end of each trip, to see how long each trip was
  • Creating a new column called day_of_week to find out what day of the week each trip was taken on
  • Deleting all rows containing a ride_length of 0:00:00 (Most of these were test rides)
  • Deleting all rows containing a negative value for ride_length
  • Replacing faulty station_name labels with Find & Replace using the corresponding station_id and matching the station_name using data from other monthly files

The 12 CSV files containing monthly data were now ready to be analyzed using R.

Combining all of the data into one data frame called year_data:

year_data <- bind_rows(sept20, oct20, nov20, dec20, jan21, 
feb21, mar21, apr21, may21, june21, july21, aug21)

year_data$date <- as.Date(year_data$started_at)


Splitting the date" column into respective day, year and month columns to easily access different aspects of the trip start time:

year_data$year <- format(as.Date(year_data$date), "%Y")


I also made 2 columns that reflect the start hour and end hour for each trip:

year_data$start_hour <- lubridate::hour(year_data$started_at)
year_data$end_hour <- lubridate::hour(year_data$ended_at)


The ride_length column was recognized as a character, but it needs to be a numeric value so I did the conversion:

year_data$ride_length <- chron(times=year_data$ride_length)

This concludes the analysis section of the case study. Based on the findings that were produced using R, I have provided a summary below, and recommendations for the new marketing campaign that Cyclistic will implement.

Summary

  • 44.6% of trips over the year are casual riders and 55.4% are members
  • The average ride length for casual riders is 29 minutes & 52 seconds and for members its 13 minutes and 52 seconds
    • The average ride length is more than double for casual members
  • The number of trips is steadily increasing from February to July and then starts decreasing drastically from August to December
    • This makes sense based on the weather patterns in Chicago
  • The number of trips increases steadily from 5 AM to 5 PM and then drops towards midnight
    • Most people are using the bike-share service during work hours
  • The number of trips taken by casual riders only surpasses that of members from 830 PM to 4 AM
  • When looking at trips based on day of the week, members take more trips from Monday to Friday, whereas casual riders take more trips on Saturday and Sunday
    • This further shows how casual riders are using the service recreationally instead of for commuting purposes
  • Streeter Dr and Grand Ave is by far the busiest station with 55,306 total trips starting at this station when
    • When looking at the top 10 stations for casual riders vs.members, this station does not appear in the top 10 for members, but it is the #1 busiest station for casual riders. So this means that overall, casual riders contribute to almost all of the traffic at the Streeter Dr and Grand Ave
  • The number of trips from the top 10 busiest stations for casual riders are a lot more varied, with some stations, like Streeter Dr and Grand Ave having a lot more trips compared to the second busiest stations
    • When looking at the top 10 busiest stations for members they are relatively consistent with the number of trips ranging from around 15,000 to 25,000.
    • This indicates that members are starting from various stations across Chicago and are not just concentrated at one station


Recommendations/Action Plan

Based on the insights generated from the data there are a few things I believe will really help Cyclistic achieve their goal of converting casual riders to members:

  • The first thing that should be done is to make casual riders aware of how they are using the service differently. I believe that casual riders are more spontaneous when compared to annual members, since they are not necessarily using the bikes to commute to work.
    • The company mentions that around 30% of total users are using Cyclistic for commuting purposes, so these individuals should already be members.
    • Casual riders may not be aware of their importance to Cyclistic, they make up 44.6% of the annual trips and their average trip length is more than double the trip length of members.
    • By acknowledging these differences, explicitly sharing this information, and showing that casual riders are crucial to the business. This can help them feel sense of importance and give them reason to stay loyal to Cyclistic.
  • The marketing strategy should focus on incentivizing casual riders to become annual members.
    • Casual riders are taking more trips during weekends and during non-working hours of the day.
    • The company should consider an alternative annual membership that provides benefits to those using the service more frequently during the weekend. This could involve a different price, or a certain price once they have taken a number of trips. It must be shown that after a number of trips as a casual rider, they are actually spending more money and getting less perks compared to a member.
    • In addition, the marketing strategy should target these users in the months before the spike in total number of trips begins. If they are targeted sometime in February, where the number of trips begins to steadily rise, they will be more enticed to become members since they are likely excited about the weather getting better and the chance to explore again.
  • Partnerships will be very important when trying to convince casual riders to become members. The results of the analysis show that casual riders frequently start their trips at Streeter Dr and Grand Ave, which is Navy Pier in Chicago. This is a major attraction in the city and explains why it is the busiest station by a large margin.
    • Partnering with various tourist attractions or restaurants in the area will help casual riders realize the benefits of being a member.
    • There could be an offer where if you eat a certain place, or by tickets for a certain attraction, they will get x % off of an annual membership.
    • On the other hand, the deal could be reversed, where having an annual membership with Cyclistic will give you perks such as 5 % select things at Navy Pier. This could also apply to Millenium Park, which is the second busiest stop for casual riders.
    • Knowing the most popular stations for casual riders also makes it easy to take this into consideration when developing the marketing campaign. Cyclistic could set up booths where people can come talk to representatives of the company about the benefits and perks of becoming a member.


I believe that by taking all of these recommendations into consideration, the marketing analytics team at Cyclistic can develop an effective marketing strategy that will target casual riders, and persuade them to become annual members. The insights generated from the trip data over the last year makes this very clear. Casual riders use the service differently, but they are just as important to the company and should be rewarded for this.
